  "prompt": "Is money laundering a crime?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a crime. It is the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\"). This typically involves three stages: **placement** (introducing the illicit funds into the financial system), **layering** (concealing the source of the funds through complex transactions), and **integration** (reintroducing the money into the economy as legitimate funds).\n\nMoney laundering is illegal because it facilitates criminal activity, such as drug trafficking, terrorism, fraud, and corruption, by allowing criminals to profit from their illegal actions while avoiding detection. Most countries have strict laws and regulations in place to combat money laundering, and individuals or organizations found guilty of it can face severe penalties, including fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment.",
